detail.content: NYU Native American + Indigenous Students Club - Home Page. The only group at New York University that represents Native American and Indigenous students.                        NYU Native American and Indigenous Students' Group                              ABOUT US  EVENTS      CLASSES  RESOURCES  CONTACT and MEMBERSHIP                                            Image: Jacob Floyd at "Docs on the Edge" after screening Tonto Plays Himself at the Cantor Film Center, NYU (2010).                                              Welcome!     Our primary mission is to form a supportive community of and for Native American and Indigenous students and scholars at New York University. Our members have a mix of backgrounds from full-bloods to people without tribal status-- everyone is welcome. The group aims to impact our school and local community by showing the breadth of talent and activities that Native & Indigenous students, staff, and scholars are involved in. We don't sit around campfires and bead shawls (though that might be fun, too): we make films about our families, we win law cases, we make sound installations, we run Multicultural Centers, we solve environmental problems, we make amazing cupcakes, we act in plays, we present papers on Freud and we study sexuality in Cuba. Once a month, we gather to eat fry bread and talk, laugh, dissent, celebrate, and occasionally watch a movie about Indians.         To sign up for our listserv: If you are part of the NYU community, browse for the Native Network through NYUhome. If you do not have an NYU email address or have problems, email the webmaster .          Note: The Native American and Indigenous Students Group at NYU is a registered All-Square student club at NYU.  We are funded and governed by student government and our leadership are Native and Indigenous students.  The club is not affiliated with any academic department at NYU.  The club is advised by staff from the Center for Student Activities, Leadership, and Service (CSALS).  No faculty or administrators or non-student members of the club or others have permission from the student club leadership and club members to represent themselves to others, in any manner, that they are a member, leader, spokesperson or representative of the club.  If you have any questions or concerns regarding this statement, please contact the club officers or our CSALS club advisor.                                                 Letters

NYU Native American + Indigenous Students Club - Events                        NYU Native American and Indigenous Students' Group                              ABOUT US  EVENTS     CLASSES  RESOURCES  CONTACT and MEMBERSHIP    Letters                                            Club members listening to a presentation given by staff from AICH .                                                  Resources!     Many announcements for NYC or NYU resources are made via the Native Network listserve. To sign up for our listserv: If you are part of the NYU community, browse for the Native Network through NYUhome. If you do not have an NYU email address or have problems, email the webmaster .          NYU Resources:     Center for Multicultural Education and Programs : The Center for Multicultural Education and Programs (The Center) produces intentional and sustained educational initiatives and campus-wide programs in the area of diversity and social justice. It is directed by an affiliate of NYU's Native and Indigenous Student's Group, Richard Chavolla. They have a Facebook page.     Frybread Friday Productions : This grant program is supported by Native students/community members for Native students/community members.It is still in its creation phases, but will be a grant program for Native and Indigenous students to produce an original work while at NYU. This could be a film, exhibition, short story, symposium, academic publication, theatre piece, concert, event, entrepreneurial project, or whatever forms and mediums students are engaging in. Stay tuned for more information.     New York City Resources:     American Indian Community House : a not-for-profit organization serving the health, social service, and cultural needs of Native Americans residing in New York City. They have a healthy presence on Facebook .     Scholarships & Internships:     People in NAISG can help you apply for or coordinate some of the scholarships and grants, including ones from tribal councils.         External Directory of Internships and Fellowships for Native Americans     External Financial Aid Directory for Native American Students     The Udall Scholarship : This $5,000 scholarship is awarded to 80 undergraduate sophomores and juniors pursuing careers related to Tribal Public Policy, Native Health Care, or the Environment (you must be a Native American/Alaska Native to be eligible in the first two categories).     Native American Congressional Internship : This ten-week summer internship in Washington, D.C. is for Native American and Alaska Native students who wish to learn more about the federal government and issues affecting Indian Country. The internship is fully funded: the Foundation provides round-trip airfare, housing, per diem for food and incidentals, and a stipend at the close of the program.     Washington Internships for Native Students (WINS) : offers students of sovereign American Indian, Alaska Native, and Native Hawaiian (AI/AN/NH) nations the opportunity to build leadership skills while living, studying, and interning in Washington, DC.     Arthur C. Parker Scholarship & NSF Scholarships for Archaeological Training for Native Americans and Native Hawaiians: These $4000 scholarships will support high school seniors, college undergraduates, and graduate students to attend and training programs in archaeological methods offered by accredited colleges or universities.     Native American Graduate Fellowships in Resource Management : The purpose of the innovative program is to advance the educational level and qualifications of Native American students so they might contribute to the better management of their own tribal lands and resources as well as planetary resources in general. The participants may elect to pursue selected advanced training or follow a more structured two-year program with the intent of earning a Master of Science degree.     Chancellor's Postdoctoral Fellowships in American Indian Studies , University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign:  This fellowship program provides a stipend, a close working association with AIS faculty, and assistance in furthering the fellow's development as a productive scholar. Applicants should have an ongoing research project that promises to make a notable contribution to American Indian and Indigenous Studies.     Native Artist-in- Residence at the The Indian Arts Research Center (IARC): offers four artist in residence fellowships annually to advance the work of mature and emerging Native artists. Each fellowship includes a monthly stipend, housing, studio space, a supplies allowance, and travel reimbursement to and from SAR.     Resident Research Fellowships at School for Advanced Research (SAR) : summer, six- and nine-month Resident Scholar Fellowships are awarded to scholars who have completed their research and analysis in the social sciences, humanities, and Native arts and who need time to reflect, debate, and write.     Indian Arts Research Center Internship : The Indian Arts Research Center annually offers paid nine-month internships to Native individuals who are recent college graduates, current graduate students, or junior museum professionals interested in furthering their collections management experience and enhancing their intellectual capacity for contributing to the expanding field and discourse of museum studies. The internship includes a monthly stipend, housing, book allowance, travel to one professional conference, and reimbursable travel to and from SAR.     Delta Kappa Gamma Society International Native American Grant : grants to Native American women who are pursuing studies and who plan to work in Education or another service field.     Library Resident Research Fellowship : The American Philosophical Society Library offers short-term residential fellowships for conducting research in its collections. While this is not specifically for Native Americans, the library does have more than a thousand hours of audio recordings of Native American languages and a dedicated Native anthropology collection.     Henry Roe Cloud Dissertation Writing Fellowship in American Indian and Indigenous Stud ies : intended to develop American Indian Studies at Yale and by extension throughout the academy by facilitating the completion of the doctorate by scholars working on pressing issues related to the American Indian experience. Scholars working on topics in Indigenous Studies that relate to the study of North American Indians are also encouraged to apply. Support includes an annual stipend of $26,000, full access to Yale facilities and services, office space, and health care coverage.      Frances Crawford Marvin American Indian Scholarship : The American Indians Committee of National Society, Daughters of the American Revolution, awards scholarships to help Native American students of any age, any tribe, in any state striving to get an education. Bases of awards are financial need, academic achievement.     Smithsonian Native American Awards Program : For Community scholar residencies, visiting student scholar residencies, and Internships are available for individuals to pursue independently designed research projects in association with Smithsonian Staff. Stipends, travel allowance included.     Charles A. Eastman Dissertation Fellowship for Native American Scholars : Supports graduate scholars for a year-long residency at Dartmouth College and provides an opportunity for scholars who plan a career in higher education to finish their dissertations.  In addition, fellows will participate in classroom activities with scholars who are dedicated to undergraduate teaching.     American Indian Science and Engineering Society Scholarships : AISES offer a variety of scholarships that are intended to partially defray tuition and other educational expenses.     Four Directions Summer Research Program : For undergraduate/graduate Native American students interested in medicine or biomedical research. This program is an opportunity to conduct basic science research with Harvard faculty and to network with peers and colleagues.  No previous research experience is required, though introductory biology is recommended.     New York Needs You : NYNY aims to level the playing field for first-generation college students in New York City through its intensive career development and leadership training Fellowship.     Phillips Fund for Native American Research : Grants for research in Native American linguistics, ethnohistory, and the history of studies of Native Americans, in the continental United States and Canada. The committee prefers to support the work of younger scholars who have received the doctorate. Applications are also accepted from graduate students for research on master’s theses or doctoral dissertations.     Frances C. Allen Fellowship for Women of American Indian Heritage : For fellowships to study at the Newberry Library, including the D'Arcy McNickle Center for American Indian History, in Chicago. One month to one year, up to $2,000.     Seventh Generation Fund for Indian Development : for Arts and Cultural Expression, Environmental Health and Justice, Human Rights, Sustainable Communities, Intergenerational Leadership, and Women’s Leadership. Grants from $500 to $5,000 are provided three times per year to Native communities that address one or more of the Fund’s program areas.                                                     Letters
